Answer:
✅ YES — in MOST binary search problems, if you use an ans variable, you CAN use i <= j with i = mid + 1 and j = mid - 1.
❌ But NOT in every single binary search problem.
There are clear conditions when this is valid and when it is NOT.

Now I’ll explain slowly, clearly, and honestly, because this doubt is fundamental. 
1️⃣ What using ans REALLY means  

When you use an extra variable ans, you are saying:

“Even if I discard mid, I am NOT losing the answer,
because I already stored it safely.”

So this pattern is valid:

if condition(mid):
    ans = mid      # save answer
    j = mid - 1    # discard mid safely
else:
    i = mid + 1


And this loop is valid:

while i <= j:
 

This is completely correct logic.

2️⃣ When this works PERFECTLY (very important) 

You can safely use
i <= j + mid ± 1 + ans
when ALL these are true 👇

✅ Condition A

You can explicitly check whether mid satisfies the condition.

✅ Condition B

Once mid satisfies the condition, all answers on one side are worse, so you search only the other side.

✅ Condition C

The problem wants:

smallest valid index

largest valid index

minimum / maximum value

first / last occurrence

minimum speed / capacity / days etc.

🔥 Examples where this ALWAYS works

Lower Bound (with ans)

Upper Bound (with ans)

Koko Eating Bananas

Capacity to Ship Packages

Nth root / Square root

Aggressive Cows

Binary search on answer problems

👉 In all these, your statement is TRUE.

3️⃣ When this DOES NOT work (this is the key)

There are some problems where using ans + discarding mid is NOT safe, even if mid “looks like” an answer.

❌ Peak Element (LC 162)
❌ Find Minimum in Rotated Sorted Array (clean version)
❌ First True / Last True (without storing)
WHY?

Because in these problems:

You cannot finalize mid immediately

You do NOT know if a better answer exists on the SAME side

The answer must be found by converging pointers, not by storing a snapshot

In Peak Element:

You cannot say “this mid is final peak” safely

You only know direction, not finality

Storing ans early can be misleading

That’s why the clean solution keeps mid.

4️⃣ Very important clarification (this will remove confusion)

❗ Using ans is a design choice, not a rule.

If the problem allows final confirmation at mid → ans works

If the problem only gives directional information → ans is risky

5️⃣ So your sentence — corrected precisely

You said:

“if I use ans then I can do i <= j and mid ± 1 in every sum”

❌ That statement is slightly incorrect
✅ Correct version (THIS is the truth):

If the problem allows final confirmation of mid,
then using ans + i <= j + mid ± 1 is always safe.

6️⃣ One golden test you should ask yourself (VERY IMPORTANT)

Before choosing the style, ask this ONE question:

❓ “When mid satisfies the condition,
can I GUARANTEE it is a valid answer and safely discard it?”

✅ Yes → use ans, i <= j, mid ± 1

❌ No → keep mid, use i < j

This single question decides everything.

7️⃣ Final clarity in ONE TABLE
Problem nature      	Can finalize mid?	Use ans?	     Loop
Lower / Upper Bound	        ✅ Yes	       ✅ Yes	         i<=j
Binary search on answer	    ✅ Yes	       ✅ Yes	         i <= j
Peak Element	            ❌ No	       ❌ Better not	  i < j
Direction-based search	    ❌ No	          ❌	           i < j
🧠 Final one-line takeaway (memorize this)

Using ans lets you discard mid — but ONLY if mid can be finalized as an answer.

