interview style

i<j vs i<=j by itself

It depends only on what mid tells you.

2️⃣ Type-A: CONFIRMABLE problems (ans is VALID)

👉 At mid, you can say YES or NO with certainty

Meaning:

If condition is true at mid

Then mid is definitely a valid answer

No extra information needed

Examples:

Lower Bound

Upper Bound

Koko Eating Bananas

Capacity to Ship Packages

Square root / Nth root

Example (Lower Bound)
nums[mid] >= x


This tells you completely:

mid satisfies the requirement

it will remain valid forever

So you can safely do:

ans = mid
j = mid - 1


✅ ans is safe
✅ discarding mid is safe

3️⃣ Type-B: DIRECTIONAL problems (ans is NOT safe)

👉 At mid, you do NOT know the answer,
you only know which side to go.

This is the key idea.

🔴 What “directional” means (very important)

“Directional” means:

The condition at mid does NOT confirm mid is an answer
It only tells you where an answer must exist

Peak Element (your known example)

Condition used:

nums[mid] > nums[mid+1]


What does this tell you?

❌ It does NOT tell you:

“mid is a peak”

✅ It only tells you:

“a peak exists on the LEFT side (including mid)”

So mid is not confirmed.

That’s why:

you don’t store ans

you don’t discard mid blindly

you just move in that direction

4️⃣ Another directional example (not peak)
Find Minimum in Rotated Sorted Array (clean version)

Condition:

if nums[mid] <= nums[j]:


What does this tell you?

❌ It does NOT tell you:

“mid is the minimum”

✅ It only tells you:

“the minimum lies on the LEFT side”

Again:

mid is not confirmed

ans is unsafe

must converge pointers

5️⃣ Why ans FAILS in directional problems (core reason)

Let me say this very clearly:

In directional problems,
mid is only a signpost, not a destination

If you store ans = mid, you may store:

something that is not actually valid

something that just helped you choose a direction

That’s exactly what happened in peak:

slope info ≠ peak confirmation

6️⃣ Why these problems are sometimes called “bidirectional”

You may hear:

directional

bidirectional

slope-based

monotonic on sides

All mean roughly this:

From mid, you can move LEFT or RIGHT,
but you cannot FINALIZE the answer at mid.

That’s it.

